s&#x02019; actions. It is still possible that attrition is systematically different in the treatment and control groups. In particular, we would be concerned if those with higher weight for age z-scores were less likely to get weighed at midline and endline in the performance pay treatment group as in <xref rid="bib0175" ref-type="bibr">Jacob (2005)</xref>. This could signal a change in the composition of the groups because of the treatment and we would need to correct for non-random attrition. Table A2 in Supplementary material columns (1) to (4) provide evidence that between rounds 2 and 3 (Baseline-II and Endline-I), there are no significant differential attrition rates and the attrition itself is not correlated with higher z-scores in the treatment groups. In the medium term, there is lower attrition in the performance pay group suggesting that the children are less likely to drop out or be absent from day care centers, with no evidence of non-random attrition across groups based on health.<xref rid="fn0010" ref-type="fn">2</xref><table-wrap id="tbl0015" position="float"><label>Table 2b</label><caption><p>Compliance and attrition rates.</p></caption><alt-text id="at0025">Table 2b</alt-text><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th colspan="2" align="left"/><th align="left">Control</th><th align="left">Performance Pay</th><th align="left">Fixed Bonus</th><th align="left">Total</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align="left" rowspan="3">Baseline 1</td><td align="left">children weighed</td><td align="left">2231</td><td align="left">1028</td><td align="left">1035</td><td align="left">4294</td></tr><tr><td align="left">children whose mothers quizzed</td><td align="left">1949</td><td align="left">892</td><td align="left">896</td><td align="left">3737</td></tr><tr><td align="left">% children whose mothers quizzed</td><td align="left">0.87</td><td align="left">0.87</td><td align="left">0.87</td><td align="left">0.87</td></tr><tr><td colspan="6" align="left">&#x02